astNode.text: I found the problem and will post it here in case anyone is interested.

node.contents: The application used Hibernate along with HSQLDB, and I had created a utility class to simplify handling of EntityManagerFactories. It contained a method like this:

astNode.text: The application used Hibernate along with HSQLDB, and I had created a utility class to simplify handling of EntityManagerFactories. It contained a method like this:

elements.contents: private static javax.persistence.EntityManagerFactory getEntityManagerFactory() { if (emf == null) { Map properties = new HashMap(); properties.put("hibernate.connection.url", "jdbc:hsqldb:file:" + ConfigurationUtil.CONFIG_DIRECTORY + File.separator + "local.db"); emf = Persistence.createEntityManagerFactory("FPU", properties); } return emf; }

units.rawText: private static javax.persistence.EntityManagerFactory getEntityManagerFactory() { if (emf == null) { Map properties = new HashMap(); properties.put("hibernate.connection.url", "jdbc:hsqldb:file:"+ ConfigurationUtil.CONFIG_DIRECTORY + File.separator + "local.db"); emf = Persistence.createEntityManagerFactory("FPU", properties); } return emf; }

node.contents: What happened was that during startup several threads called this method, causing a number of EntityManagerFactories to be created. This lead to the application not shutting down correctly. Making the above method synchronized solved the problem.
